00:00:16.030 --> 00:00:18.580
Thanks for your help.

00:00:18.580 --> 00:00:22.980
In this video we will cover all you need to
know about ‘first hop redundancy protocols’,

00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:25.289
or FHRPs.

00:00:25.289 --> 00:00:30.000
This isn’t the name of a specific protocol,
it’s a type of protocol, and there are three

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.530
FHRPs you should be aware of for the CCNA.

00:00:33.530 --> 00:00:36.800
Let’s check the exam topics list.

00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:42.640
Here it is, topic 3.5, ‘describe the purpose
of first hop redundancy protocol’, I think

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:45.350
there should be an ‘s’ on the end there.

00:00:45.350 --> 00:00:48.920
There is no mention of configuration, so you
don’t need to worry about about configuring

00:00:48.920 --> 00:00:51.420
any of the FHRPs for the exam.

00:00:51.420 --> 00:00:56.699
However, in this video I will show you basic
configurations for one of the FHRPs, so you

00:00:56.699 --> 00:00:59.799
can try it out in the next lab video.

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:04.610
Even if you don’t need to know the configurations
for the exam, getting a little hands-on practice

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:08.100
will help you understand how these FHRPs work.

00:01:08.100 --> 00:01:11.049
Here’s what we’ll cover in today’s video.

00:01:11.049 --> 00:01:16.380
First up, I’ll introduce the purpose of
first hop redundancy protocols.

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:19.360
Then I’ll introduce three different FHRPs.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:23.540
HSRP, hot standby router protocol.

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:27.310
VRRP, virtual router redundancy protocol.

00:01:27.310 --> 00:01:31.340
And GLBP, gateway load balancing protocol.

00:01:31.340 --> 00:01:35.729
It may seem like a lot to learn about three
different protocols in one video, but you

00:01:35.729 --> 00:01:41.850
just need to be able to make basic comparisons
of each, you don’t need to know them in-depth.

00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:46.499
Finally we’ll spend a few minutes learning
some basic configurations of HSRP, hot standby

00:01:46.499 --> 00:01:47.799
router protocol.

00:01:47.799 --> 00:01:52.659
After the quiz at the end of the video I will
feature a bonus question from Boson ExSim

00:01:52.659 --> 00:01:57.329
for CCNA, a set of practice exams for the
CCNA.

00:01:57.329 --> 00:02:03.219
I studied using ExSim when preparing for both
my CCNA and CCNP exams, and I highly recommend

00:02:03.219 --> 00:02:05.130
that you do too.

00:02:05.130 --> 00:02:08.060
To get ExSim, follow the link in the video
description.

00:02:08.060 --> 00:02:11.730
Okay, let’s get started.

00:02:11.730 --> 00:02:16.990
I used this same diagram back in Day 20 when
talking about spanning tree protocol, to demonstrate

00:02:16.990 --> 00:02:21.380
the concept and importance of redundancy in
networks.

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:25.850
For example, if there is only one connection
to the Internet and it fails due to a hardware

00:02:25.850 --> 00:02:31.190
failure or something else, these PCs will
no longer be able to reach the Internet.

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:35.850
In your home, losing Internet access for some
time would be frustrating, but probably not

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:37.610
a disaster.

00:02:37.610 --> 00:02:41.350
For most modern businesses, however, it would
be a big problem.

00:02:41.350 --> 00:02:45.770
So, we can use redundant connections to the
Internet like this.

00:02:45.770 --> 00:02:51.790
Notice I’ve added some device names and
IP addresses in the 172.16.0.0/24 network

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:54.710
to make things easier to talk about.

00:02:54.710 --> 00:02:59.890
Now if this connection fails PC1 can use this
alternate path to the Internet.

00:02:59.890 --> 00:03:04.050
This could be, for example, a slower and cheaper
connection that is only used until the main

00:03:04.050 --> 00:03:06.750
connection is recovered.

00:03:06.750 --> 00:03:10.730
But let’s stop and think about this, because
it’s not so simple.

00:03:10.730 --> 00:03:17.390
In this network, let’s say R1’s IP address
172.16.0.254 is configured as the default

00:03:17.390 --> 00:03:18.940
gateway.

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:25.870
So that means each PC is configured with the
172.16.0.254 address as its default gateway.

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:31.040
So, anytime these PCs need to send traffic
outside of the local subnet, they will send

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:33.930
it to the default gateway, R1.

00:03:33.930 --> 00:03:38.820
But what happens if R1 goes down for some
reason, perhaps a hardware failure?

00:03:38.820 --> 00:03:43.879
Fortunately, there is a backup router connected
to the Internet, R2.

00:03:43.879 --> 00:03:45.280
But there’s a problem here.

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:47.590
Can you identify the problem?

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:51.350
Pause the video and think about it for a minute.

00:03:51.350 --> 00:03:54.430
Okay, the problem is here.

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:59.530
The PCs’ default gateway is still set to
.254, R1’s address.

00:03:59.530 --> 00:04:04.380
Although R2 is available as a backup, the
PCs don’t know that R1 is down and that

00:04:04.380 --> 00:04:08.240
they should switch to using R2 as their default
gateway.

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:12.570
If a PC needs to send traffic over the Internet,
it will continue to try to send the traffic

00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:13.730
to R1.

00:04:13.730 --> 00:04:19.470
So, how can we cause R2 to automatically become
the new default gateway if R1 can no longer

00:04:19.470 --> 00:04:20.540
be used?

00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:25.680
That’s the role of a first-hop redundancy
protocol, an FHRP.

00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:29.790
Here’s a brief explanation of FHRPs from
Wikipedia.

00:04:29.790 --> 00:04:35.760
‘A first hop redundancy protocol (FHRP)
is a computer networking protocol which is

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:40.980
designed to protect the default gateway used
on a subnetwork by allowing two or more routers

00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:46.710
to provide backup for that address; in the
event of failure of an active router, the

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:51.720
backup router will take over the address,
usually within a few seconds.’

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:55.870
The name ‘first-hop’ redundancy protocol
is used because the default gateway is the

00:04:55.870 --> 00:05:00.650
‘first hop’, the first router in the path
to whatever destination the PC is sending

00:05:00.650 --> 00:05:01.970
traffic to.

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:05.270
Here’s how FHRPs do this.

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:13.590
The two routers share a VIP, a virtual IP
address, for example 172.16.0.252.

00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:18.250
You configure the PCs in the network to use
that virtual IP as their default gateway,

00:05:18.250 --> 00:05:20.900
instead of the actual IP address of R1.

00:05:20.900 --> 00:05:24.930
Now, the routers have to negotiate their roles
with each other.

00:05:24.930 --> 00:05:26.250
How do they do that?

00:05:26.250 --> 00:05:31.170
They send multicast ‘Hello’ messages to
each other, like this.

00:05:31.170 --> 00:05:34.780
Okay, so what roles did they negotiate?

00:05:34.780 --> 00:05:39.670
Well, one of them, let’s say R1, will become
the active router.

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:43.570
The other, R2, will become the standby router.

00:05:43.570 --> 00:05:49.170
Note that the actual terms, like active and
standby, vary depending on which FHRP is being

00:05:49.170 --> 00:05:53.430
used, because as I showed you before there
are a few different FHRPs.

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:59.730
So, R1 is the active, meaning it will act
as the default gateway for the network.

00:05:59.730 --> 00:06:06.330
R2 is the standby, meaning it will not function
as the default gateway unless R1 fails.

00:06:06.330 --> 00:06:10.550
If R1 does fail, it will automatically take
over the role as default gateway.

00:06:10.550 --> 00:06:16.830
So, let’s say we set up our FHRP here in
this network, and now PC1 needs to send some

00:06:16.830 --> 00:06:19.460
traffic to a destination in another network.

00:06:19.460 --> 00:06:21.790
Here’s what PC1 is thinking.

00:06:21.790 --> 00:06:25.570
I need to send traffic to a destination in
another network.

00:06:25.570 --> 00:06:31.240
My default gateway is 172.16.0.252, but I
don’t know the MAC address yet.

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:36.170
I will send an ARP request to learn the MAC
address of 172.16.0.252.

00:06:36.170 --> 00:06:42.430
I haven’t mentioned ARP in a while in this
course, but remember that it is used to learn

00:06:42.430 --> 00:06:46.120
the MAC address of a particular IP address.

00:06:46.120 --> 00:06:50.990
In order for PC1 to encapsulate the packet
in a frame destined for the default gateway,

00:06:50.990 --> 00:06:53.740
it has to know the default gateway’s MAC
address.

00:06:53.740 --> 00:07:01.300
So, PC1 will make an ARP request like this,
saying ‘Hi 172.16.0.252.

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:03.070
This is 172.16.0.1.

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:06.390
What’s your MAC address?’.

00:07:06.390 --> 00:07:08.730
Remember that the ARP request message is broadcast.

00:07:08.730 --> 00:07:13.780
So, it will be sent over the network like
this, reaching all hosts.

00:07:13.780 --> 00:07:19.010
Fortunately spanning tree prevents a broadcast
storm by disabling some of the switch interfaces.

00:07:19.010 --> 00:07:27.120
So, both R1 and R2 have received the ARP request,
and they both share the same virtual IP address,

00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:30.520
172.16.0.252, the one in the ARP request.

00:07:30.520 --> 00:07:31.980
What happens now?

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:33.860
Which will send the ARP reply?

00:07:33.860 --> 00:07:40.040
R1 is the active router and R2 is the standby
router, so you can probably guess that R1

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:42.419
will send the ARP reply.

00:07:42.419 --> 00:07:43.570
And that is correct.

00:07:43.570 --> 00:07:47.490
R1 will send a unicast ARP reply like this.

00:07:47.490 --> 00:07:50.040
‘Hi 172.16.0.1.

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:51.910
This is 172.16.0.252.

00:07:51.910 --> 00:07:57.490
My MAC address is...’, and then it will
tell PC1 the virtual MAC address.

00:07:57.490 --> 00:08:04.150
That’s right, not only is a virtual IP address
used, but a virtual MAC address too.

00:08:04.150 --> 00:08:08.970
Each FHRP uses a different virtual MAC address,
and I will introduce them later.

00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:14.300
So, the ARP reply is sent to PC1.

00:08:14.300 --> 00:08:17.669
Now PC1 knows the MAC address of its default
gateway.

00:08:17.669 --> 00:08:23.790
So let’s say PC1 needs to send some traffic
to the IP address 8.8.8.8, which is a Google

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:25.650
server by the way.

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:30.139
What will the source and destination fields
of the frame and packet be?

00:08:30.140 --> 00:08:35.200
The source IP will be PC1’s, 172.16.0.1.

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:40.050
The destination IP will be the Google server,
8.8.8.8.

00:08:40.050 --> 00:08:43.289
The source MAC will be PC1’s MAC address.

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:48.240
And the destination MAC address will be the
virtual MAC address used by the FHRP.

00:08:48.240 --> 00:08:53.899
The frame will be sent to R1, and then the
packet will be sent over the Internet.

00:08:53.899 --> 00:08:55.730
Now what if R1 goes down?

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:58.389
There is no default gateway for the network.

00:08:58.389 --> 00:09:02.470
But after a few seconds, R2 will think ‘I
haven’t received any ‘Hello’ messages

00:09:02.470 --> 00:09:07.670
from R1 recently...I will become the Active
router!’.

00:09:07.670 --> 00:09:10.120
So R2 is now the active router.

00:09:10.120 --> 00:09:14.980
But how does it tell the other devices to
send traffic to it instead of R1?

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:20.319
Note that the end hosts, the PCs, actually
don’t have to change their ARP tables.

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:27.460
The entry in the PC’s ARP table is like
this, mapping the virtual IP address 172.16.0.252

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:29.400
to the virtual MAC address.

00:09:29.410 --> 00:09:34.329
So, what needs to be updated to make traffic
start going through R2?

00:09:34.329 --> 00:09:36.189
The answer is the switches.

00:09:36.189 --> 00:09:40.790
R2 needs to make the switches update their
MAC address tables.

00:09:40.790 --> 00:09:43.779
Remember how switches update their MAC address
table.

00:09:43.779 --> 00:09:48.399
When they receive a frame they check the source
MAC address field, and use that to update

00:09:48.399 --> 00:09:50.589
the information in the MAC address table.

00:09:50.589 --> 00:09:56.440
So, R2 needs to send frames with a source
MAC address of the virtual MAC address.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:10:02.519
To do this, it will send ‘gratuitous ARP’
replies.

00:10:02.519 --> 00:10:06.670
Gratuitous ARP is probably outside of the
scope of the CCNA, but here’s a very brief

00:10:06.670 --> 00:10:09.279
explanation.

00:10:09.279 --> 00:10:13.279
Gratuitous ARP messages are ARP replies sent
without being requested.

00:10:13.279 --> 00:10:19.110
Normally ARP replies are sent in reply to
an ARP request, but in gratuitous ARP, the

00:10:19.110 --> 00:10:22.540
ARP reply messages are sent without receiving
an ARP request.

00:10:22.540 --> 00:10:27.699
Here’s another difference between gratuitous
ARP and regular ARP replies.

00:10:27.699 --> 00:10:34.230
The frames are broadcast to the MAC address
of all Fs, but normal ARP replies are unicast.

00:10:34.230 --> 00:10:38.089
Because they are broadcast, all switches will
receive the frames and update their MAC address

00:10:38.089 --> 00:10:39.149
table.

00:10:39.149 --> 00:10:43.790
So, R2 will send gratuitous ARPs like this.

00:10:43.790 --> 00:10:47.870
They will be broadcast throughout the network,
and again spanning-tree protocol will prevent

00:10:47.870 --> 00:10:49.810
a broadcast storm.

00:10:49.810 --> 00:10:52.699
The switches will then update their MAC address
tables.

00:10:52.699 --> 00:10:58.619
SW2 will learn that it can now reach the virtual
MAC address via this interface, SW1 will learn

00:10:58.619 --> 00:11:04.370
the same thing, and so will SW3 and SW4.

00:11:04.370 --> 00:11:08.800
Now R2 is the active router, and all of the
switches have updated their MAC address tables.

00:11:08.800 --> 00:11:15.759
Let’s say PC1 wants to send traffic to the
same Google server, 8.8.8.8, again.

00:11:15.759 --> 00:11:18.869
The frame and packet are exactly the same
as before.

00:11:18.869 --> 00:11:25.160
Source IP is PC1’s, Destination IP is the
Google server, source MAC is PC1’s, and

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:27.399
destination MAC is the Virtual MAC.

00:11:27.399 --> 00:11:31.809
However, this time the frame will be sent
to R2, which will send the packet out over

00:11:31.809 --> 00:11:33.259
the Internet.

00:11:33.259 --> 00:11:36.819
Now, what if R1 comes online again?

00:11:36.819 --> 00:11:39.019
Will it become the active router once again?

00:11:39.019 --> 00:11:42.619
No, it will become the standby router.

00:11:42.619 --> 00:11:48.540
Like I said about the DR and BDR in OSPF,
FHRPs are ‘non-preemptive’.

00:11:48.540 --> 00:11:52.920
The current active router will not automatically
give up its role, even if the former active

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:54.290
router returns.

00:11:54.290 --> 00:11:59.210
However, although this is the default behavior,
you can change this setting to make R1 preempt

00:11:59.210 --> 00:12:05.709
R2 and take back its active role automatically,
so R2 will become the standby router again.

00:12:05.709 --> 00:12:11.910
Okay, so that was a basic overview of how
first hop redundancy protocols, FHRPs, work.

00:12:11.910 --> 00:12:17.110
I haven’t talked about any specific FHRPs
yet, but most of that information applies

00:12:17.110 --> 00:12:19.339
to all of them.

00:12:19.339 --> 00:12:24.480
Before moving on to explain a few specific
FHRPs, here’s a quick review.

00:12:24.480 --> 00:12:29.510
A virtual IP is configured on the two routers,
and a virtual MAC is generated for the virtual

00:12:29.510 --> 00:12:31.350
IP.

00:12:31.350 --> 00:12:35.670
Each FHRP uses a different format for the
virtual MAC address, I’ll cover those MAC

00:12:35.670 --> 00:12:38.730
addresses in the next section.

00:12:38.730 --> 00:12:41.559
An active router and a standby router are
elected.

00:12:41.559 --> 00:12:46.759
Again, different FHRPs use different terms,
and some support what’s called an ‘active-active’

00:12:46.759 --> 00:12:51.730
setup, with two active routers at the same
time, but I’ll explain more later.

00:12:51.730 --> 00:12:57.910
Next, end hosts in the network are configured
to use the virtual IP as their default gateway.

00:12:57.910 --> 00:13:02.339
The active router replies to ARP requests
using the virtual MAC address, so traffic

00:13:02.339 --> 00:13:05.690
destined for other networks will be sent to
it.

00:13:05.690 --> 00:13:08.879
It functions as the default gateway for the
network.

00:13:08.879 --> 00:13:13.519
If the active router fails, the standby becomes
the next active router.

00:13:13.519 --> 00:13:17.519
The new active router will send gratuitous
ARP messages so that switches will update

00:13:17.519 --> 00:13:19.699
their MAC address tables.

00:13:19.699 --> 00:13:23.089
It now functions as the default gateway for
the network.

00:13:23.089 --> 00:13:27.110
If the old active router comes back online,
by default it won’t take back its role as

00:13:27.110 --> 00:13:28.410
the active router.

00:13:28.410 --> 00:13:30.540
It will become the standby router.

00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:35.329
This is like the DR and BDR in OSPF, they
don’t give up their roles automatically

00:13:35.329 --> 00:13:38.339
even if another router is configured with
a higher priority.

00:13:38.339 --> 00:13:44.149
But, in FHRPs you can configure ‘preemption’,
so that the old active router does take back

00:13:44.149 --> 00:13:46.829
its old role if it comes back online.

00:13:46.829 --> 00:13:49.920
Okay, sorry for the wall of text.

00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:54.230
Before moving on to a few specific FHRPs,
I recommend watching the previous section

00:13:54.230 --> 00:13:58.709
once more to make sure you understand the
basics of how FHRPs work.

00:13:58.709 --> 00:14:00.430
Now let’s move on.

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:05.620
N ow I’ll give a brief overview of
three major FHRPs.

00:14:05.620 --> 00:14:10.290
The functionality of each is very similar,
so this section will be quite brief, but make

00:14:10.290 --> 00:14:12.720
sure you learn these details for the exam.

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:18.029
First up, HSRP, Hot Standby Router Protocol.

00:14:18.029 --> 00:14:23.309
HSRP is Cisco proprietary, so it only runs
on Cisco devices.

00:14:23.309 --> 00:14:26.769
You can’t run it on Juniper routers, for
example.

00:14:26.769 --> 00:14:29.959
In HSRP, an active and standby router are
elected.

00:14:29.959 --> 00:14:35.149
These are the two terms I used previously,
but you’ll see the next FHRP uses different

00:14:35.149 --> 00:14:37.579
terms.

00:14:37.579 --> 00:14:42.430
There are two versions of HSRP, version 1
and version 2.

00:14:42.430 --> 00:14:47.699
Version 2 adds IPv6 support, and increases
the number of ‘groups’ that can be configured.

00:14:47.699 --> 00:14:51.980
You’ll see what a group is when we configure
HSRP later.

00:14:51.980 --> 00:14:59.160
In our example today, there was just one subnet,
172.16.0.0/24, and one VLAN.

00:14:59.160 --> 00:15:03.600
But in situations with multiple subnets and
VLANs, you’ll need to configure a virtual

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:09.010
IP address for each subnet, because each subnet
needs its own default gateway.

00:15:09.010 --> 00:15:13.620
Each of those virtual IPs is configured in
a separate HSRP group.

00:15:13.620 --> 00:15:18.170
Anyway, as I said you’ll see how that works
later.

00:15:18.170 --> 00:15:21.339
Remember how I explained that the routers
communicate with each other by sending multicast

00:15:21.339 --> 00:15:23.179
hello messages?

00:15:23.179 --> 00:15:24.899
These are the addresses used.

00:15:24.899 --> 00:15:32.329
224.0.0.2 for version 1, and 224.0.0.102 for
version 2.

00:15:32.329 --> 00:15:37.740
It may seem not so important, but try to remember
these addresses for the test.

00:15:37.740 --> 00:15:40.759
Next up, the virtual MAC address formats.

00:15:40.759 --> 00:15:45.430
These are tougher to remember, but make sure
you remember them for the exam.

00:15:45.430 --> 00:15:50.040
Use the flashcards, try writing them from
memory, whatever you have to do to remember

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:51.060
them.

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:58.889
So, version 1 uses 0000 0c07 ac, followed
by the group number.

00:15:58.889 --> 00:16:05.079
So, in my previous example let’s say I configured
the virtual IP address in group 1.

00:16:05.079 --> 00:16:09.730
If using HSRP version 1, what would be virtual
MAC address be?

00:16:09.730 --> 00:16:16.850
It’s 0000 0c07 ac01, because the group number
is 1.

00:16:16.850 --> 00:16:28.329
Now, HSRP version 2 uses the format 0000 0c9F
Fxxx, again xxx is the group number.

00:16:28.329 --> 00:16:33.290
Note that 3 hexadecimal digits are now available
instead of 2, so there are more group numbers

00:16:33.290 --> 00:16:34.290
available.

00:16:34.290 --> 00:16:40.279
Anyway, if group number 1 is used, what would
the virtual MAC address be in HSRP version

00:16:40.279 --> 00:16:41.730
2?

00:16:41.730 --> 00:16:47.549
It’s 0000 0c9f f001.

00:16:47.549 --> 00:16:52.799
One last point, in a situation with multiple
subnets/VLANs, you can configure a different

00:16:52.799 --> 00:16:56.230
active router in each subnet to load balance.

00:16:56.230 --> 00:16:59.910
Remember what I said in previous videos about
spanning-tree protocol?

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:04.490
You can configure a different root bridge
in each VLAN so traffic is load balanced over

00:17:04.490 --> 00:17:05.490
the switches.

00:17:05.490 --> 00:17:11.620
Well, when you configure multiple HSRP groups,
one for each subnet and VLAN, you can configure

00:17:11.620 --> 00:17:15.189
a different active router in each subnet and
VLAN.

00:17:15.189 --> 00:17:21.049
For example, R1 could be the active router
in VLAN1 and standby in VLAN2, and R2 could

00:17:21.049 --> 00:17:26.370
be the standby in VLAN1 and active in VLAN2.

00:17:26.370 --> 00:17:30.600
This is probably beyond what you need to know
for the CCNA, but let me briefly demonstrate

00:17:30.600 --> 00:17:31.600
the concept.

00:17:31.600 --> 00:17:38.720
Let’s say VLAN1 is assigned to hosts in
the 172.16.1.0/24 subnet.

00:17:38.720 --> 00:17:41.180
PC1 and PC3 are in VLAN1.

00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:50.799
R1 and R2 have their own IP addresses in VLAN1,
but they also share the virtual IP 172.16.1.252,

00:17:50.799 --> 00:17:53.559
which is used as the default gateway of the
subnet.

00:17:53.559 --> 00:17:58.299
R1 is the active router and R2 is the standby
router.

00:17:58.299 --> 00:18:03.480
Then, 172.16.2.0/24 is the subnet for VLAN2.

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:06.080
PC2 and PC4 are in VLAN2.

00:18:06.080 --> 00:18:14.090
R1 and R2 have their own IP addresses in VLAN2,
connecting to the switches using ‘router-on-a-stick’.

00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:21.190
They also share the virtual IP address 172.16.2.252,
which is used as the default gateway for the

00:18:21.190 --> 00:18:22.190
subnet.

00:18:22.190 --> 00:18:27.019
R2 is the active router and R1 is the standby
router.

00:18:27.019 --> 00:18:32.690
Now traffic can be load balanced over the
two paths, VLAN1 using R1 and VLAN2 using

00:18:32.690 --> 00:18:37.639
R2 as the default gateway of the subnet, and
each subnet has a standby router waiting if

00:18:37.639 --> 00:18:39.580
the active router fails.

00:18:39.580 --> 00:18:44.159
So, that’s a basic overview of HSRP.

00:18:44.159 --> 00:18:47.889
Although it can’t load balance within a
single subnet, you can configure a different

00:18:47.889 --> 00:18:52.529
active router in each subnet so that traffic
is load balanced between the routers.

00:18:52.529 --> 00:18:57.160
Let’s move on to the next FHRP.

00:18:57.160 --> 00:19:02.090
Next up is VRRP, Virtual Router Redundancy
Protocol.

00:19:02.090 --> 00:19:07.910
Unlike HSRP, it’s an open standard, so it
can be run on devices from any maker.

00:19:07.910 --> 00:19:12.360
Cisco routers run it too, so you can use either
HSRP or VRRP.

00:19:12.360 --> 00:19:19.190
Honestly, in terms of functionality they are
nearly identical, with just a few differences.

00:19:19.190 --> 00:19:24.210
Instead of an active and standby router, a
master and backup router are elected.

00:19:24.210 --> 00:19:27.730
The function is the same, just the names are
different.

00:19:27.730 --> 00:19:34.120
Master is equivalent to HSRP’s active, and
backup is equivalent to HSRP’s standby.

00:19:34.120 --> 00:19:39.700
The IPv4 multicast address used is different
as well, 224.0.0.18.

00:19:39.700 --> 00:19:45.020
Again, use the flashcards to remember little
details like this.

00:19:45.020 --> 00:19:47.720
The virtual MAC address format is different,
too.

00:19:47.720 --> 00:19:54.700
0000 5e00 01, followed by the VRRP group number.

00:19:54.710 --> 00:19:57.870
Let’s try a bit more of a challenge.

00:19:57.870 --> 00:20:02.370
What if I configured VRRP group 200, instead
of group 1.

00:20:02.370 --> 00:20:04.840
What would the virtual MAC address be?

00:20:04.840 --> 00:20:07.970
You have to convert 200 to hexadecimal.

00:20:07.970 --> 00:20:13.490
Pause the video to try that, do a Google search
if you don’t remember how hexadecimal works.

00:20:13.490 --> 00:20:21.789
Okay, the answer is 0000 5e00 01c8.

00:20:21.789 --> 00:20:26.070
Hexadecimal c8 is equal to 200 in decimal.

00:20:26.070 --> 00:20:31.950
Just like HSRP, although VRRP can’t perform
load-balancing for hosts in a single subnet,

00:20:31.950 --> 00:20:36.070
it can load balance between different subnets
by configuring a different master router in

00:20:36.070 --> 00:20:37.470
each subnet.

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:43.809
Here’s the same diagram as before, showing
load-balancing between the two subnets.

00:20:43.809 --> 00:20:47.289
All that’s different is that ‘master’
and ‘backup’ are used instead of ‘active’

00:20:47.289 --> 00:20:49.929
and ‘standby’.

00:20:49.929 --> 00:20:55.039
Before moving on, I just want to mention one
point separate from FHRPs.

00:20:55.039 --> 00:21:02.440
Notice that all hosts in VLAN1 are in the
same subnet, 172.16.1.0/24, and all hosts

00:21:02.440 --> 00:21:08.389
in VLAN2 are in the same subnet, 172.16.2.0/24.

00:21:08.389 --> 00:21:11.549
This is how subnets and VLANs are used.

00:21:11.549 --> 00:21:16.441
Subnets divide the network at Layer 3, and
VLANs divide the network at Layer 2, and they

00:21:16.441 --> 00:21:20.230
work together, each subnet being its own VLAN.

00:21:20.230 --> 00:21:26.080
You might have noticed that throughout this
course, but I just wanted to point it out.

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:32.570
Before moving on to the last FHRP, here’s
a comparison chart of HSRP and VRRP.

00:21:32.570 --> 00:21:35.390
In terms of functionality, they’re nearly
the same.

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:42.159
But remember the different terminology, multicast
IP addresses, and virtual MAC addresses.

00:21:42.159 --> 00:21:47.510
Also remember that HSRP is Cisco proprietary,
whereas VRRP is an open standard that can

00:21:47.510 --> 00:21:51.240
run on any network device that supports it.

00:21:51.240 --> 00:21:55.100
Next up, we’ll take a look at GLBP.

00:21:55.100 --> 00:22:01.149
The final FHRP you should be aware of is GLBP,
Gateway Load Balancing Protocol.

00:22:01.149 --> 00:22:05.610
This one is a bit different than HSRP and
VRRP.

00:22:05.610 --> 00:22:10.710
Like HSRP, it is Cisco proprietary, it only
runs on Cisco devices.

00:22:10.710 --> 00:22:17.500
Here’s the big difference: it load balances
among multiple routers within a single subnet.

00:22:17.500 --> 00:22:24.860
For example, if PC1 and PC2 are both in VLAN1,
PC1 can use R1 as its default gateway, and

00:22:24.860 --> 00:22:28.299
PC2 can use R2 as its default gateway.

00:22:28.299 --> 00:22:33.580
This is different than HSRP and VRRP, in which
all hosts in the same subnet must use the

00:22:33.580 --> 00:22:36.950
same router as the default gateway for the
subnet.

00:22:36.950 --> 00:22:43.429
In GLBP, a single AVG, Active Virtual Gateway,
is elected for the subnet.

00:22:43.429 --> 00:22:51.470
Then, up to four AVFs, active virtual forwarders,
are assigned by the AVG, and the AVG itself

00:22:51.470 --> 00:22:54.210
can be an AVF also.

00:22:54.210 --> 00:22:58.759
Each AVF acts as the default gateway for a
portion of the hosts in the subnet.

00:22:58.759 --> 00:23:02.919
So, load balancing is achieved within a single
subnet.

00:23:02.919 --> 00:23:10.519
The multicast IPv4 address is 224.0.0.102,
same as HSRP version 2.

00:23:10.519 --> 00:23:17.919
The virtual MAC address format is 0007 b400,
followed by the GLBP group number and the

00:23:17.919 --> 00:23:18.919
AVF number.

00:23:18.919 --> 00:23:25.850
For example, what is the virtual MAC address
of AVF number 1 in GLBP group 1?

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:30.490
It’s 0007 b400 0101.

00:23:30.490 --> 00:23:37.820
So, the functions of GLBP are a bit more complicated
than HSRP and VRRP, but for the purposes of

00:23:37.820 --> 00:23:43.320
the CCNA remember that GLBP allows multiple
active routers to load balance traffic within

00:23:43.320 --> 00:23:49.960
a single subnet, and remember the multicast
IP address and the virtual MAC address format.

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:55.520
It might seem not so important, but for the
CCNA exam definitely remember the IP and MAC

00:23:55.520 --> 00:23:56.710
addresses.

00:23:56.710 --> 00:24:01.280
Here’s that chart again, with GLBP filled
in.

00:24:01.280 --> 00:24:07.520
If you remember the basic characteristics
of HSRP, VRRP, and GLBP, and memorize the

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:12.549
information in this chart, you’ll be ready
to answer any questions about FHRPs on the

00:24:12.549 --> 00:24:14.500
CCNA exam.

00:24:14.500 --> 00:24:18.990
However, as a little extra, I’m going to
show you some very basic configurations for

00:24:18.990 --> 00:24:24.160
HSRP, so we can try it out in a lab in the
next video.

00:24:24.160 --> 00:24:28.830
Although configuring HSRP isn’t part of
the CCNA exam topics, getting some hands-on

00:24:28.830 --> 00:24:32.169
experience will help you understand how it
works.

00:24:32.169 --> 00:24:37.190
So let’s do some basic configurations for
HSRP.

00:24:37.190 --> 00:24:41.340
To fit everything on the page and show the
CLI at the same time I’ve simplified the

00:24:41.340 --> 00:24:42.340
network.

00:24:42.340 --> 00:24:47.840
We’ll be focusing on configuring R1 and
R2 to use HSRP to provide a redundant default

00:24:47.840 --> 00:24:53.070
gateway address for the 172.16.0.0/24 subnet.

00:24:53.070 --> 00:24:57.710
I’ve already configured all of the interface
IP addresses, so we just need to configure

00:24:57.710 --> 00:24:59.929
HSRP.

00:24:59.929 --> 00:25:04.669
Note that I’m using .254 as the virtual
IP this time, instead of .252.

00:25:04.669 --> 00:25:08.370
So, let’s get started configuring R1.

00:25:08.370 --> 00:25:14.350
HSRP is configured directly on the interface,
G0/0 in this case.

00:25:14.350 --> 00:25:18.220
Make sure you configure it on the correct
interface, the one connected to the network

00:25:18.220 --> 00:25:21.009
it is acting as the default gateway for.

00:25:21.009 --> 00:25:25.220
HSRP is configured with the STANDBY command.

00:25:25.220 --> 00:25:28.730
I used the question mark to see what options
are available.

00:25:28.730 --> 00:25:34.130
There are many more than this, but the one
we want to use is this one, group number.

00:25:34.130 --> 00:25:39.040
Note that HSRP version 1 is the default, so
the range of groups available is 0 through

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:41.520
255.

00:25:41.529 --> 00:25:46.929
If using HSRP version 2, this range would
be 0 through 4095.

00:25:46.929 --> 00:25:50.390
Actually, let me show you how to change it
to version 2.

00:25:50.390 --> 00:25:53.799
The command is STANDBY VERSION 2.

00:25:53.799 --> 00:25:57.669
If I check the STANDBY command again, you
can see that the group number range is now

00:25:57.669 --> 00:26:01.379
0 through 4095.

00:26:01.379 --> 00:26:07.259
This simple network is using just a single
VLAN, VLAN1, so I chose HSRP group number

00:26:07.259 --> 00:26:08.259
1.

00:26:08.259 --> 00:26:13.409
You don’t have to do this, it’s not a
rule, but I like to match the HSRP group number

00:26:13.409 --> 00:26:16.460
to the VLAN number used for the subnet.

00:26:16.460 --> 00:26:21.059
Note that this group number does have to match
between the two routers, that’s important.

00:26:21.059 --> 00:26:24.960
So, I used the question mark again to check
the options available here.

00:26:24.960 --> 00:26:27.010
We’ll go over three.

00:26:27.010 --> 00:26:30.269
IP, PREEMPT, and PRIORITY.

00:26:30.269 --> 00:26:38.559
First up, you configure the virtual IP with
this command, STANDBY, group number, IP, followed

00:26:38.559 --> 00:26:42.550
by the IP address you want to use as the default
gateway.

00:26:42.550 --> 00:26:49.210
Then I used the PRIORITY command, as you can
see the range is 0 to 255, and I set R1’s

00:26:49.210 --> 00:26:51.159
priority to 200.

00:26:51.159 --> 00:26:52.639
What does priority do?

00:26:52.639 --> 00:26:56.860
It’s used to determine which router will
be the active router.

00:26:56.860 --> 00:26:59.360
The active router is determined in this order.

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:05.019
First, the router with the highest HSRP priority
in the group will become the active router.

00:27:05.019 --> 00:27:07.549
The default priority is 100.

00:27:07.549 --> 00:27:11.769
If the routers have the same priority, the
router with the highest IP address will become

00:27:11.769 --> 00:27:13.740
the active router.

00:27:13.740 --> 00:27:23.419
In this case R1’s IP address, 172.16.0.253,
is higher than R2’s IP address, 172.16.0.252.

00:27:23.419 --> 00:27:28.790
So, even without configuring the priority
R1 would still become the active router, but

00:27:28.790 --> 00:27:30.779
I configured it anyway.

00:27:30.779 --> 00:27:34.049
Finally, I enabled ‘preemption’.

00:27:34.049 --> 00:27:38.620
Enabling the PREEMPT command causes the router
to take the role of active router, even if

00:27:38.620 --> 00:27:43.590
another router already has the role, although
the preempting router must have a higher priority

00:27:43.590 --> 00:27:45.830
or IP address.

00:27:45.830 --> 00:27:50.309
For example, let’s say R1 is the active
router and R2 is the standby router.

00:27:50.309 --> 00:27:55.259
If an error causes R1 to restart, R2 will
become the active router.

00:27:55.259 --> 00:28:01.019
When R1 comes back online, if preemption is
not enabled R2 will remain the active router

00:28:01.019 --> 00:28:03.129
and R1 will be the standby.

00:28:03.129 --> 00:28:08.071
However, with preemption enabled R1 will take
back its role as the active router, because

00:28:08.071 --> 00:28:10.759
it has the higher priority.

00:28:10.759 --> 00:28:13.999
Note that you only need to configure preemption
on the router that you want to become the

00:28:13.999 --> 00:28:15.590
active router.

00:28:15.590 --> 00:28:20.331
Even if I don’t configure preemption on
R2, R1 will still be able to preempt R2 and

00:28:20.331 --> 00:28:23.039
take back the active role.

00:28:23.039 --> 00:28:24.360
Now let’s configure R2.

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:30.620
First up, I enabled HSRP version 2 on R2’s
G0/0 interface.

00:28:30.620 --> 00:28:37.169
This is important, HSRP version 1 and version
2 are not compatible, so if R1 uses version

00:28:37.169 --> 00:28:42.490
2, R2 must use version 2 also or there will
be problems.

00:28:42.490 --> 00:28:49.309
Next I configured the same virtual IP as on
R1, 172.16.0.254.

00:28:49.309 --> 00:28:53.740
The next two commands, setting the priority
and preemption, are actually unnecessary.

00:28:53.740 --> 00:28:58.879
R1 already has a higher priority than R2,
and preemption doesn’t need to be enabled

00:28:58.879 --> 00:29:00.669
on the standby router.

00:29:00.669 --> 00:29:05.140
But I configured them anyway, so the configuration
is consistent between the two routers, but

00:29:05.140 --> 00:29:08.429
it doesn’t really matter.

00:29:08.429 --> 00:29:12.029
Finally let’s take a look at the output
of SHOW STANDBY.

00:29:12.029 --> 00:29:16.570
This is the output from both R1 and R2, let’s
just take a look at R1.

00:29:16.570 --> 00:29:22.740
First up, notice the HSRP group number of
1 and that version 2 is being used.

00:29:22.740 --> 00:29:25.850
The state is active, because R1 is the active
router.

00:29:25.850 --> 00:29:30.210
Here the virtual IP address we configured
is displayed.

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:34.929
These two lines display the virtual MAC address,
it’s the default one.

00:29:34.929 --> 00:29:37.100
Here are the HSRP timers.

00:29:37.100 --> 00:29:41.070
We didn’t configure these so they are the
default values.

00:29:41.070 --> 00:29:45.509
Preemption is enabled, because we configured
STANDBY 1 PREEMPT.

00:29:45.509 --> 00:29:49.570
Active router is local, because R1 itself
is the active router.

00:29:49.570 --> 00:29:55.289
The standby router is 172.16.0.252, which
is R2.

00:29:55.289 --> 00:29:59.520
And finally here is the priority value of
200 that we configured.

00:29:59.520 --> 00:30:03.850
If you want to take a look at the output of
the command for R2 also, pause the video.

00:30:03.850 --> 00:30:09.211
Okay, that’s all we’ll cover about HSRP
configuration, in the lab video we’ll get

00:30:09.211 --> 00:30:12.080
more hands on.

00:30:12.080 --> 00:30:16.610
Before moving on to the quiz, let’s review
what we covered in this video.

00:30:16.610 --> 00:30:21.769
First I gave an introduction to the purpose
and basic function of FHRPs, which is to provide

00:30:21.769 --> 00:30:24.740
a redundant default gateway for a subnet.

00:30:24.740 --> 00:30:33.270
Then, I briefly introduced three different
FHRPs, HSRP, VRRP, and GLBP.

00:30:33.270 --> 00:30:37.059
Make sure to learn the basic characteristics
of each, and use the chart to memorize their

00:30:37.059 --> 00:30:41.710
multicast IP addresses and virtual MAC addresses.

00:30:41.710 --> 00:30:45.710
Then I introduced some very basic HSRP configuratons.

00:30:45.710 --> 00:30:49.590
You probably won’t be asked about these
commands on the exam, but getting some hands

00:30:49.590 --> 00:30:54.640
on practice will help you understand the topic,
so in the next video we’ll do a simple HSRP

00:30:54.640 --> 00:30:58.350
lab, taking a look at preemption and such.

00:30:58.350 --> 00:31:00.559
Here are the commands we used.

00:31:00.559 --> 00:31:05.619
STANDBY VERSION 2, to configure the router
to use HSRP version 2.

00:31:05.619 --> 00:31:11.299
STANDBY IP, to set the virtual IP address
that will be used as the default gateway.

00:31:11.299 --> 00:31:15.740
STANDBY PRIORITY, to help control which router
becomes the active router.

00:31:15.740 --> 00:31:20.330
And STANDBY PREEMPT, to cause the active router
to take its role back if it recovers from

00:31:20.330 --> 00:31:22.600
a failure.

00:31:22.600 --> 00:31:26.860
Remember to watch until the end of today’s
quiz for a bonus question from Boson ExSim

00:31:26.860 --> 00:31:32.330
for CCNA, by far the best practice exams you
can get for the CCNA.

00:31:32.330 --> 00:31:35.169
You can get Boson ExSim from the link in the
video description.

00:31:35.169 --> 00:31:39.769
Okay, let’s go to question 1 of the quiz.

00:31:39.769 --> 00:31:44.059
Which of the following is an HSRP version
1 virtual MAC address?

00:31:44.059 --> 00:31:54.280
A, B, C, or D. Pause the video now to think
about your answer.

00:31:54.280 --> 00:32:01.080
The answer is D, 0000 0c07 acab.

00:32:01.080 --> 00:32:10.309
The HSRP version 1 virtual MAC address format
is 0000 0c07 ac, followed by the group number,

00:32:10.309 --> 00:32:12.490
in this case AB.

00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:14.480
What is AB in decimal?

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:21.650
It’s 171, so in this case HSRP group number
171 was used.

00:32:21.650 --> 00:32:28.419
As for the incorrect answers, options A and
C are HSRP version 2 virtual MAC addresses,

00:32:28.419 --> 00:32:32.610
and option B does not follow any FHRP virtual
MAC address format.

00:32:32.610 --> 00:32:36.720
Let’s go to question 2.

00:32:36.720 --> 00:32:40.059
Which of the following is a VRRP virtual MAC
address?

00:32:40.059 --> 00:32:48.480
A, B, C, or D. Pause the video to think about
your answer.

00:32:48.480 --> 00:32:55.159
The answer is A, 0000 5e00 010a.

00:32:55.159 --> 00:33:03.820
The VRRP virtual MAC address format is 0000
5e00 01, followed by the group number.

00:33:03.820 --> 00:33:06.539
What is hexadecimal 0a in decimal?

00:33:06.539 --> 00:33:13.379
It’s 10, so in this case VRRP was configured
using group number 10.

00:33:13.379 --> 00:33:20.700
Option B is a GLBP virtual MAC address, option
C is an HSRP version 2 virtual MAC address,

00:33:20.700 --> 00:33:24.919
and option D does not follow any FHRP virtual
MAC address format.

00:33:24.919 --> 00:33:29.980
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:33:29.980 --> 00:33:33.529
Which of the following are valid VRRP router
roles?

00:33:33.529 --> 00:33:34.529
Select two.

00:33:34.529 --> 00:33:36.169
A, active.

00:33:36.169 --> 00:33:37.929
B, backup.

00:33:37.929 --> 00:33:39.970
C, active virtual gateway.

00:33:39.970 --> 00:33:41.580
D, master.

00:33:41.580 --> 00:33:43.210
E, standby.

00:33:43.210 --> 00:33:45.909
Or F, active virtual forwarder.

00:33:45.909 --> 00:33:52.010
Pause the video to think about your answers.

00:33:52.010 --> 00:33:55.279
The answers are B, backup and D, master.

00:33:55.279 --> 00:33:59.919
A, active and E, standby are HSRP router roles.

00:33:59.919 --> 00:34:06.279
C, active virtual gateway and F, active virtual
forwarder, are GLBP router roles.

00:34:06.279 --> 00:34:09.050
VRRP uses master and backup routers.

00:34:09.050 --> 00:34:13.580
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:34:13.580 --> 00:34:18.120
When the HSRP standby router becomes the new
active router, what kind of messages does

00:34:18.120 --> 00:34:19.330
it send?

00:34:19.330 --> 00:34:20.800
Select the best answer.

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:24.140
A, HSRP hello messages.

00:34:24.140 --> 00:34:26.860
B, gratuitous ARP messages.

00:34:26.860 --> 00:34:30.020
C, ARP request messages.

00:34:30.020 --> 00:34:32.740
Or D, ARP reply messages.

00:34:32.740 --> 00:34:39.010
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:34:39.010 --> 00:34:42.210
The answer is B, gratuitous ARP.

00:34:42.210 --> 00:34:47.950
Some other answers are not totally incorrect,
but are not the best answer, let me explain.

00:34:47.950 --> 00:34:52.350
In Cisco’s questions, at the end it usually
says ‘select the best answer’.

00:34:52.350 --> 00:34:56.500
That’s because some of the options aren’t
totally incorrect, however they aren’t the

00:34:56.500 --> 00:34:58.170
best answer.

00:34:58.170 --> 00:35:02.020
For example, option A is ‘HSRP Hello’.

00:35:02.020 --> 00:35:05.310
Routers using HSRP always send Hello messages.

00:35:05.310 --> 00:35:10.180
So, when the HSRP standby router becomes the
new active router, it will continue sending

00:35:10.180 --> 00:35:14.880
HSRP hello messages, so A isn’t totally
incorrect.

00:35:14.880 --> 00:35:19.450
However B is the better answer, because it
only sends these gratuitous ARP messages when

00:35:19.450 --> 00:35:22.090
it becomes the new active router.

00:35:22.090 --> 00:35:23.870
How about D, ARP reply?

00:35:23.870 --> 00:35:29.370
I told you that gratuitous ARP messages are
a kind of ARP reply, so D isn’t totally

00:35:29.370 --> 00:35:30.370
incorrect.

00:35:30.370 --> 00:35:33.950
However, B is the better answer because it’s
more specific.

00:35:33.950 --> 00:35:39.480
So, when taking the CCNA exam make sure you’re
selecting the best answer, even if some of

00:35:39.480 --> 00:35:42.180
the other options seem like they might be
correct.

00:35:42.180 --> 00:35:46.330
Let’s go to question 5.

00:35:46.330 --> 00:35:50.120
Which of the following statements accurately
describes HSRP?

00:35:50.120 --> 00:35:51.890
Select the best answer.

00:35:51.890 --> 00:35:57.530
A, it allows you to configure a different
default gateway address on each end host.

00:35:57.530 --> 00:36:02.900
B, it allows multiple routers to load-balance
traffic for hosts in a subnet.

00:36:02.900 --> 00:36:08.080
C, it provides a redundant default gateway
address for hosts in a subnet.

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:12.730
Or D, each router selects a unique virtual
IP and MAC address.

00:36:12.730 --> 00:36:17.860
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:36:17.860 --> 00:36:22.630
The answer is C, it provides a redundant gateway
for hosts in a subnet.

00:36:22.630 --> 00:36:27.120
Although you can configure a different active
router in each subnet to provide load balancing,

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:30.620
it doesn’t provide load balancing for hosts
in a single subnet.

00:36:30.620 --> 00:36:35.980
To do that, you would need to use Cisco’s
GLBP, gateway load balancing protocol.

00:36:35.980 --> 00:36:38.390
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:36:38.390 --> 00:36:43.250
Let’s move on to a bonus question in Boson
ExSim for CCNA.

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:48.060
Okay, here's today's Boson ExSim practice
question.

00:36:48.060 --> 00:36:51.950
By the way, I noticed that you can zoom in
on ExSim, so hopefully this is easier for

00:36:51.950 --> 00:36:53.930
you to read now.

00:36:53.930 --> 00:36:54.930
So here's the question.

00:36:54.930 --> 00:36:57.690
Why of the following statements are true regarding
HSRP?

00:36:57.690 --> 00:36:59.000
Select two choices.

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:03.380
Okay, so I'll let you read these options yourself.

00:37:03.380 --> 00:37:08.640
Pause the video here, read the options, and
select the two correct choices.

00:37:08.640 --> 00:37:12.330
Okay, hopefully you got the answers.

00:37:12.330 --> 00:37:13.550
So let's check them.

00:37:13.550 --> 00:37:19.030
A, one router is elected as the master router,
and all other routers are placed in the backup

00:37:19.030 --> 00:37:20.030
state.

00:37:20.030 --> 00:37:26.590
That is incorrect, master and backup, that
terminology is used for VRRP, not HSRP.

00:37:26.590 --> 00:37:34.000
B, in an HSRP group only one virtual IP address
is used, but multiple virtual MAC addresses

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:35.000
are used.

00:37:35.000 --> 00:37:37.050
That is also incorrect.

00:37:37.050 --> 00:37:41.770
In a single HSRP group only one virtual MAC
address is used.

00:37:41.770 --> 00:37:48.240
Okay, C. One router is elected as the active
router and another router is elected as the

00:37:48.240 --> 00:37:50.220
standby router.

00:37:50.220 --> 00:37:53.740
That is correct, I believe, about HSRP.

00:37:53.740 --> 00:38:01.710
D, in an HSRP group only one virtual IP address
and one virtual MAC address is used.

00:38:01.710 --> 00:38:03.220
That is correct also.

00:38:03.220 --> 00:38:06.740
I think, but let's check option E as well.

00:38:06.740 --> 00:38:11.400
All routers in an HSRP group can participate
by forwarding a portion of the traffic.

00:38:11.400 --> 00:38:16.160
Okay, that is not true for HSRP, but it is
true for GLBP.

00:38:16.160 --> 00:38:19.760
Okay, so I think C and D are correct.

00:38:19.760 --> 00:38:22.520
Let's click on show answer.

00:38:22.520 --> 00:38:24.700
And that is correct.

00:38:24.700 --> 00:38:28.340
